This is what will happen when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates.
The interest rate will rise and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise and the economy will enter a recession.
That's what we know.
What we don’t know is how long it will be and how long it will take.
In economics, history offers little clue to timeliness.
After the first interest rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That’s why U.S. central bank officials have so strongly emphasized that investors should not focus on when the interest rate starts to rise but on the trajectory of the time it takes to normalize.
Indeed, there are multiple variables in the game.
But in the end, market players might find that all the turmoil about raising the interest rate has been exaggerated.
“The Fed’s first interest rate hike after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the era of ‘cheap money,’” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to more normal but still low levels to be the seismic shock that everyone seems to be afraid of.
However, it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Below we present how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation the market has faced in recent months, anticipating interest rate rises can volatilize things for a while.
But at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a trend for capital returns to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first rise, which may again reflect monetary policy lag,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what will happen after the Fed’s rises.
Specifically, in the last 35 years, the market has risen sharply - by about 14 percent - heading towards the interest rate increase, quite invariable in the period of 250 days after (average climb of 2.6%) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron Management by the strategist No.
Deutsche said the impact on equities tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate rise cycle and profits are starting to decline.
Recession is a reality of economic life but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, gross domestic product will approach its historic low for a Fed interest rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Even though in the second quarter of 2015 the figure was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Rising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and raise the question “if this time is different,” Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing year-round for a growth decision by the Fed, with all eyes set on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an interest rate increase at this meeting, futures trading indicates a probability of only 25%.
“In our study since 1950, all interest rate growth cycles so far have been in a super profit growth cycle, with GDP eclipsing pre-recession peaks very quickly after recovery began,” the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strangely slow recovery after the worst recession in the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and it has reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income has also been volatile given that the market expects an interest rate increase and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster in the case of bonds than in the case of equities when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it appears that the benefits change direction as soon as the first increase/decline in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate rise cycle, bond yields drop immediately,” Deutsche said.
Strategists Charles Schwab believe that these interest rate increases will bring short-term and long-term bonds closer to profitability, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds do better in such an environment, although "we are still cautious about forcing profitability," Kathy Jones, a Schwab fixed income analyst, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adjusted to Fed policy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in estimated inflation, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of a more rigorous monetary policy," Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is straighter, the spread of the average credit interest rate has expanded and volatility has risen – all market characteristics when the Fed tightens policy.
Broadly speaking, U.S.-based companies will benefit from higher interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
Multinationals with large debts will suffer because the increase of the dollar will lead to the cost of their products in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial interest rate hike,” Goldman Sachs said in a customer report.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed those with weak balance sheets after each of the 1994, 1999 and 2004 interest rate increases by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high capital and low volatility stocks also outperformed similar companies with lower quality, with an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points), respectively.
Debt will become an important issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also benefit from the increase in the dollar.
Those who save might also have a win-win, although experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
