To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal gave an example of Romanian products before and after accession to the European Union: "In Romania, before you entered the EU, you had good vegetables and meat".
To enter the EU you had to pass health laws that are not good for vegetables and meat.
Production and agriculture end up in the service of supermarkets, as is the case in France.
Music is the same, it’s the same logic.
Les Dissonances makes tomatoes maybe not too beautiful, but when we cut them they are real tomatoes.
In an ideal world, this music should return to the center and the institutions and industries that manage this system understand that music does not need to be sold, but needs to be shared, and this can be done starting with education policy.
"If we consider - as the Koreans, the Chinese, the Japanese do - that Western music is one of the most beautiful things in humanity, we reintroduce its learning in school, we reintroduce concerts on television and through this education we would no longer need to sell musical by-products," Grimal said.
Certainly, there are things in classical music education that remain very communist, this is everywhere, it is something very militarized.
It depends on this discipline if we compare a musician to a soldier, or if we form a musician who will play an instrument, being, above all, a musician.
We’re talking about a completely different education, if we want to train a soldier, it has to be somehow, if we want to train a musician, it’s totally different.
In your opinion, what is more dangerous, a soldier or a musician?” asked the French artist, smiling.
Grimal shows that, for artists, the reward of a different way of making music comes precisely from overcoming this status of "soldier", overcoming what "they think are their limits": "Musicians discover at a certain moment that they are not soldiers, and that is why after the concert they come out smiling".
