At the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it is time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank’s meeting room, will be a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, Fed President, and her colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The central bank has been given a double task by Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, to be announced on Tuesday, that will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be rid of the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect since the end of 2008.
Even though most data indicate a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by raising the benchmark rate to federal funds — even by just a quarter percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise interest rates, the rising uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them a reason to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed’s decision, which in itself is causing instability in the financial market.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg anticipated an interest rate hike this week.
But financial markets are expecting the Fed to postpone, with a key indicator showing the likelihood of growth at just 30 percent.
This would indicate a fall on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers would soften the blow by promising that it would take a long time for the next rise.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The uptick was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising for the Fed to raise the interest rate at this time,” Lonski said.
If Fed policymakers were to do so, “they should act deeply in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.”
Other experts said an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared on track to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward slowing monetary tightening that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected an interest rate hike this year despite objections from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was strong this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Salary gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them given the tension in the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began fibrillating at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below its record high in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market declined somewhat this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed policymakers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the timing of interest rate hikes.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and the news of the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, we would be more firm at the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he expects that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they have almost no data to rely on aftermath of events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s major interests, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
The mere allusion by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “narrow” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at wealth management firm Investnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that “the Fed has an overreacting history to changes in the financial market that appear to be unrelated to economic underpinnings.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported interest rate hikes, gave an example of the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that hit Asia prompted the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the limited identification implications for U.S. development," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to the declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market quake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate board.
The latest turmoil does not rise to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to be afraid of an interest rate hike because the markets have been upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until something changes in that regard, I don’t think it should take premature action.
