Weight-loss surgery could be helpful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those undergoing nonsurgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgeon, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight relative to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy — in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received nonsurgical diabetes treatments remained at nearly the same level, namely 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured in 36% and partially in 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, controlling blood pressure, triglycerides, and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored the blood level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the group treated with medical methods, it was maintained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycaemic control” – reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels – did not reduce the mortality rate at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the gastrectomy group in the sleeve, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), experienced more considerable decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c 7% (3.1% versus 2.1%), and had a higher probability of complete remission (16% versus 2.1%) and had a higher probability of complete remission (46).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of people with high weight in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, Faculty of Medicine – Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic aspect for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in the procedure.
“This is the point at which this paper is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the group with lower BMI,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking the weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long before we’re urging people to take this seriously,” she said.
I think once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies and predisposed them to obesity and diabetes, it’s extremely difficult to get back to normal.
