The government approved on Wednesday the "National Strategy on Immigration for the period 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage that Romania is going through as part of the efforts to modernize the process of managing immigration on national territory", according to a press release.
The strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and policy directions that reflect policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
Considering the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are considered for the unitary and coherent management of the situations determined by the possible occurrence of an influx of illegal immigrants into Romania, generated by political, social, economic or military crisis situations.
"The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay particular attention to citizens from states with migratory potential or that may harm national security," the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in the areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the residence of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the appropriate application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the territory of Romania for third-country nationals who meet employment needs, facilitating access for third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for the fields and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers that it is "a means by which concrete activities are established that lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migration phenomenon".
Romania, in a European top on the labor market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the largest increase in total labour costs among EU Member States in the second quarter of the year compared to the same period in 2014, according to data published on Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
The index refers to employers' personnel expenses.
Thus, between April and June 2015, the total labour cost rose by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania ranks third in the EU at rising labour cost
The highest increases were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU countries where the hourly labour cost fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The increase in labour costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to the increase in the hourly labour cost in industry and services, with 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania recorded an advance of 5.8% of the hourly labour cost.
