What button will appear soon
Millions of Facebook users have become accustomed to the "Like" button, and now the representatives of the social network are preparing another opposite, that of "Dislike".
On Tuesday, Mark Zuckerberg, co-founder and CEO of the company, announced on his account that this button will be available soon, informs the New York Times on the blog.
Zuckerberg said the “Dislike” button would show a nuance of what a user feels rather than just an option.
However, his announcement raised the issue that Facebook could become a less friendly place.
Zuckerberg said he wants to avoid moments when someone posts on his account about an important event in his life, and someone else will “dislike” it.
Users of the network, which has reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long demanded to have the opportunity to express negative emotions or empathize with something sad.
Mark Zuckerberg said it was not very comfortable for people to "like" current events, such as the refugee crisis or the death of a family member.
“You may not feel comfortable liking that post,” the Facebook spokesperson said.
The new Facebook button has not been well received by everyone.
“There is already enough hatred on Facebook and social media,” Atiq Haneef of Afghanistan said on the New York Times Facebook page, where the article on the topic was posted.
"I'm going to 'dislike' the 'dislike' button," he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist from Atlanta, has argued that there is nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, a social media analyst at eMarketer, said it was hard to imagine that a single button could transmit a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she argues, the election campaign in America is approaching, and the "Dislike" button would create a total disaster.
