Corbyn, Brexit and the Future of Europe
Due to economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity enjoyed in recent decades cannot continue the same in the years to come.
By Saturday, probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn was.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the Labour Party in the UK, many wonder how much it can affect our choice of a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position.
Jeremy Corbyn is Labour’s most radical leftist leader since the war.
An outspoken Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once asked Tony Blair, then prime minister, to take the royal family out of Buckingam Palace), a fierce anti-American and a nuclear sympathizer of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events by the television channel "Russia Today" and the EU's "Hamas Today" and "Hisbolism" movements).
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a real tragedy, ISIS is almost preferred to the United States.
On the model of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like what Tsipras was saying and promising in Greece until he faced the real world and economic legislatures.
The economic program of the new Labour leader foresees, among other things, massive renationalizations and the printing of money as a solution for financing development projects and covering very generous social benefits.
Sure, some may wonder why the solution with the printing of money is not unanimously adopted in the world, we would then have a general global prosperity!, but who can prevent such details.
Sure, we can tax the bankers, who have become a kind of service enemy of the left, with blood, but from what has been seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of the mandates of Mitterrand and Hollande.
The extra sums are quickly swallowed up by the generous, uncovered promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher said, “The problem with socialism is that at some point the money of others runs out.”
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance to ever become prime minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in his beliefs as the new party leader, failed miserably in the election.
And then there was still a working class in Britain, in the classical sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were significantly more influential than they are now.
Given the new industrial landscape, in which services are dominant across the workforce, and extensive automations have made the industry massively in need of highly skilled workers, Corbyn’s rhetoric has a limited appeal.
But even in opposition, it can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that Corbyn’s choice increases the chances of Brexit, or Britain’s exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of the globalization that imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric and you look at the refugee crisis that shakes the foundations of the EU, you come up with an explosive mix.
And not just for the UK.
But if the British decide after the referendum, which should take place by 2017, to leave the Union the loss of symbolic capital for the whole European project and the deep breaches created within it by the Euro crisis and now by the refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leaves room for the most worrying scenarios.
All the more so since for a whole series of member states, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which however Berlin becomes more and more the dominant actor).
True, the British business community, the City, are strong advocates of the country’s remaining in the EU.
But today’s Europe is no longer the one of the past.
There are many resentments, which are increasing in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, we even recently had a sample in the speech of Jean Clude Junker, tends increasingly to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of Member States by consulting only a few European powers, mainly with Germany.
And this is happening as electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigrant and Eurosceptic parties across the continent grows dramatically.
In other words, the negatively charged emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever before.
That’s why the Financial Times draws its conclusion when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation that departs from the national interest.
If voters make the brain decision, then the UK will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn’s victory reminds us of the power of emotion in current politics.
However, Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we are witnessing a more pronounced integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the states in the region and the periphery of interest and decision-making in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States feeds his populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity enjoyed in recent decades, the generous social benefits, can no longer continue the same in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Euro-immigration zone, both caused by hasty decisions that only took into account the integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and may affect Romania’s situation greatly.
And it’s hard to rule out anything from the point of view of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
